This issue is twofold: determine a strategy for registering mimetypes and, at a higher level, register plugins in general.

Similar to how [HyperTerm](https://hyperterm.org/) expects particular keys on an `exports` object for a plugin, I'd like to do the same with custom `Transforms` (a la [`transformime-react`](https://github.com/nteract/transformime-react)). We have one custom transform right now and I'm expecting us to support some others right out of the box. Here's what I'm expecting for a common interface:

``` js
import React from 'react';

const MIMETYPE = 'application/myMimetype+json';

export class CustomTransform extends React.Component {
  shouldComponentUpdate() {
    return false;
  }

  render() {
    const data = this.props.data.toJS();
    return (
      <CustomThing data={data} />
    );
  }
}

CustomTransform.propTypes = {
  data: React.PropTypes.any,
};

CustomTransform.MIMETYPE = MIMETYPE;

exports.transform = CustomTransform;
```

The three main points:
- A CustomTransform is a `React.Component` that expects a payload in the `data` field of the props (which is Immutable.js).
- The mimetype expected to come through on the Jupyter messaging protocol (and in the notebook format) is a static `MIMETYPE` attribute on the transform.
- `exports` has a key called `transform` with the transformer.

Registering it is then a reduction on the store:

``` js
[REGISTER_NEW_MIMETYPE]: (state, action) => {
  const { transform } = action;
  const mimetype = transform.MIMETYPE;

  return state.update('displayOrder', displayOrder => displayOrder.splice(0, 0, mimetype)
       .update('transforms', transforms => transforms.set(mimetype, transform);
}
```

Let's say I have the following records:

```
{
    "data": {
        "title": "My title",
        "tags": ["astronomie", "science", "burundi"],
        "author": {
            "username": "natim",
            "first_name": "Rémy"
        }
    }
}
```

**How can I get all records from natim?**

http://localhost:8000/v1/buckets/wiki/collections/articles/records?author.username=natim ?

If you define the following two types, or types that follow this pattern (Same model, different names). The relay node resolver resolves the incorrect name (and therefore incorrect globalID) for the type registered 2nd. 

```python
class ThingA(DjangoObjectType):
    class Meta:
        model = Thing
        name = 'ThingA'
        interfaces = (relay.Node, )

class ThingB(DjangoObjectType):
    class Meta:
        model = Thing
        name = 'ThingB'
        interfaces = (relay.Node, )
```
Query (ThingA globalID) : 
```
{
  node(id: "GhpbmdBOjE=") {
    id // "GhpbmdBOjE=" Correct!
  }
}
```
Query (ThingB globalID)
```
{
  node(id: "VGhpbmdCOjE=") {
    id // "GhpbmdBOjE=" Incorrect :(
  }
}
```

It appears that [there is some commented out code to warn about this.](https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene-django/blob/master/graphene_django/registry.py#L13-L15) However, it is commented out so I am unsure what the intention of the author was.

I am really just looking to see if this is "as designed". @syrusakbary

## My operating system is (include version):

Arch Linux (latest)

## I installed Certbot with (certbot-auto, OS package manager, pip, etc):

From OS package manager. 

```
$ certbot --version
certbot 0.19.0
```

## I ran this command and it produced this output:

```
$ certbot --renew
... normal renewal output
Please choose whether or not to redirect HTTP traffic to HTTPS, removing HTTP access.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1: No redirect - Make no further changes to the webserver configuration.
2: Redirect - Make all requests redirect to secure HTTPS access. Choose this for
new sites, or if you're confident your site works on HTTPS. You can undo this
change by editing your web server's configuration.
